when you’re not being prompted to look for

00:02:20.610 --> 00:02:22.189
it - like we just did right now.

00:02:22.189 --> 00:02:26.470
In the real world, people fall for drivel
all the time - some of us more than others.

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:30.969
Surprisingly, one of the things that seems
to be linked to our bull patty detector 5000

00:02:30.969 --> 00:02:32.019
is our political views.

00:02:32.019 --> 00:02:36.269
I know all of you instantly thought you’d
be better at detecting flim flam, but half

00:02:36.269 --> 00:02:37.779
of you aren’t going to be happy.

00:02:37.779 --> 00:02:42.879
L: In a study of 196 people published in the
journal PLOS One, researchers used the Bullshit

00:02:42.879 --> 00:02:49.609
Receptivity Scale to see how supporting democratic
versus republican candidates relates to BS.

00:02:49.609 --> 00:02:53.120
They found that participants who supported
this election cycle’s republican candidates

00:02:53.120 --> 00:02:57.939
Ted Cruz, Marco Rubio, and Donald Trump were
more likely to fall for baloney than those

00:02:57.939 --> 00:03:02.310
who supported the democratic candidates: Hillary
Clinton, Martin O’Malley, and Bernie Sanders.

00:03:02.310 --> 00:03:06.459
J: What’s more, they also found that the
participants who held more politically conservative

00:03:06.459 --> 00:03:10.659
views had a greater tendency to see meaning
in moonshine compared to those who were more

00:03:10.659 --> 00:03:12.049
politically liberal.

00:03:12.049 --> 00:03:15.590
And to clarify these are conclusions that
have been found in just one study.

00:03:15.590 --> 00:03:20.120
L: Another factor that makes people more susceptible
to falling for flimflam is their default when

00:03:20.120 --> 00:03:25.069
receiving new information - according to researchers
like Gilbert and Spinoza some people have

00:03:25.069 --> 00:03:29.370
a bias towards rating new information as true
as opposed to false.

00:03:29.370 --> 00:03:30.370
It’s their fallback.

00:03:30.370 --> 00:03:34.359
When we are mentally exhausted, we are more
likely to resort to this default.

00:03:34.359 --> 00:03:38.939
So people who lean towards believing new information
is true are more likely to fall for BS.

00:03:38.939 --> 00:03:44.230
J: In a 2015 study titled On the reception
and detection of pseudo-profound bullshit,

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:48.480
researchers found that claptrap receptivity
was positively correlated with believing in

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:52.930
conspiracies, in paranormal activity, and
the efficacy of alternative medicine.

00:03:52.930 --> 00:03:57.419
But all is not lost, researchers at The University
of Waterloo and Sheridan College, note that

00:03:57.419 --> 00:04:00.169
there are certain things that can help you
spot flapdoodle.

00:04:00.169 --> 00:04:02.730
L: One handy tool is looking for vagueness.

00:04:02.730 --> 00:04:07.180
If a statement is vague - unclear or ambiguous
in it’s meaning - you should probably probe

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:08.180
deeper.

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:12.090
They also note that certain mediums might
be more prone to BS than others Twitter, for

00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:17.370
example, which limits statements to 140 characters
might be more likely to foster hogwash than

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:18.769
something like a textbook.

00:04:18.769 --> 00:04:22.669
